textDisplay:
If you have a function that doesn't need to return anything, you use "void" as the return type. For example, say you have a functions called 'addNumbers'. This is the function:
float addNumbers(float a, float b) {
return a + b;
}
This function's return type is "float", because it needs the value of "a + b" to exit the function and "return" back to where it was called.


Now say you have a function called 'sayHi'. This is the function:
void sayHi() {
cout << "Hi" << endl;
}
This function's return type is "void", because it does not need anything to exit the function and "return" back to where it was called.

int means integer, i.e. whole numbers.
void is a type that has no possible values. If you don't want a function to return anything you can use void as the return type.
textOriginal:
*int* means _integer,_ i.e. whole numbers.
*void* is a type that has no possible values. If you don't want a function to return anything you can use void as the return type.

textDisplay:
Tony, if you come from PHP I can understand if it takes a while to get used to, but it's not really much of a problem, honestly. Sometimes it's actually useful to be able to treat variables as if they were functions and vice versa.

The only situation where I sometimes wish I could have variables with the same name as functions is inside classes. Some people solve this problem by adding m or _ to the name of their member variables, similar to your suggestion of adding $ to all variables except that it's not forced by the language. I haven't used this naming convention myself yet but it's something that I will consider for future projects.

Did you know that cout is a variable?
Did you know that endl is a function?
$cout << "hello" << endl;
textOriginal:
Tony, if you come from PHP I can understand if it takes a while to get used to, but it's not really much of a problem, honestly. Sometimes it's actually useful to be able to treat variables as if they were functions and vice versa.

The only situation where I sometimes wish I could have variables with the same name as functions is inside classes. Some people solve this problem by adding _m_ or _ to the name of their member variables, similar to your suggestion of adding $ to all variables except that it's not forced by the language. I haven't used this naming convention myself yet but it's something that I will consider for future projects.

Did you know that endl is a function?

textDisplay:
Hey you. Yes you, person watching this video. I'm going to teach you something that will help you better understand the inner workings of C++.

When Bucky says "printSomething is used before it is defined", he doesn't mean it literally. It can't be "used" if main() isn't actually running. And the perfect evidence to debunk it is that if you provide a function prototype for printSomething() that appears before main, then it will work just fine.

void printSomething();
int main(){ ... }
void printSomething(){ ... }

It's not defined yet, but now the compiler knows it exists. This is called a forward declaration. Its purpose is to announce the existence of a symbol without needing to define it. This specific type of declaration, with respect to a function, is called a function prototype. Bucky mentions this at 7:18

Symbol refers to an entity in the code that has a name, such as variables and functions.

Now here's what happens during compilation: since C++'s type system is static, the first thing the compiler does is a phase called static analysis (SA). In this phase, the compiler reads the code and checks all of the symbols, references to symbols, and their types to make sure everything makes sense. This phase is not actually necessary for compilation. It is a tool provided by the language that makes use of the type system, to aid the programmer in minimizing human error. You could technically compile code without performing SA, but doing that would be irresponsible. So, the compiler sees the symbol "printSomething" during SA, and does not recognize it. Rather than go on a witch hunt for a symbol that may or may not exist, it just prints out an error and either aborts or continues the compilation (depends on the compiler). Most compilers will continue until the end of SA and then abort, so that the programmer is given a full list of errors and warnings.

On the other hand, dynamic langs like JavaScript tend to go through with the aforementioned witch hunt, and have developed clever ways of making the lookup as efficient as possible.

After SA, a symbol table is put together and stored along with several sections like .rodata (read-only data), .text (machine code), or .bss (uninitialized data). This information comes together in the form of an object file.

For a more detailed overview, see this article, table w.3 <http://www.tenouk.com/ModuleW.html>

textDisplay:
main() is special in many ways.
- It is invoked automatically when the program starts.
- You are not allowed to invoke it yourself.
- It shall not be overloaded.
- It automatically returns 0 if nothing is explicitly returned.
- Reaching the end of main() terminates the whole program, even if there are still other threads running.
textOriginal:
main() is special in many ways.
 - It is invoked automatically when the program starts.
 - You are not allowed to invoke it yourself.
 - It shall not be overloaded.
 - It automatically returns 0 if nothing is explicitly returned. 
 - Reaching the end of main() terminates the whole program, even if there are still other threads running.

textDisplay:
It's a good way of separating code into smaller pieces. Normally you put code that does one specific task inside a function, and then you can just call that function whenever you want to carry out that task.

Functions should be named in a way, so that when you call the function, it describes what will happen, but you don't need to bother your brain thinking about how it does it.

Functions can also help getting rid of repeated code. If you have the same (or almost the same) code repeated in multiple places there is a great chance that if you make a change you forget or fail to update the code correctly everywhere which could lead to bugs. By using a function you only need to make the change in one place.

Functions can also help getting rid of repeated code. If you have the same (or almost the same) code repeated in multiple places there is a great chance that if you make a change you forget or fail to update the code correctly everywhere which could lead to bugs. By using a function you only need to make the change in one place.

textDisplay:
Printing is not the same as returning. The function prints some text but it doesn't return any value. To return something from a function you use the return keyword. The returned value can then be retried and used from the place where function was called.

Here is a simple example of a function that returns an int and shows how you might use it.

int square(int x)
{
return x * x;
}

int main()
{
cout << "Please enter a number: ";
int num;
cin >> num;
cout << "The square of " << num << " is " << square(num) << ".\n";

return 0;
}

textDisplay:
@ismael cruz
A class kinda is a prototype. It's like if you combined a prototype and a structure.

class.h:
class Class {
  public:
    void someFunction();
}

class.cpp:
void Class::someFunction(){ ... }

class.h tells another file that uses it, that there exists a class type called Class, and that it has a function named someFunction.

when class.cpp is compiled, the implementation is defined, and when another file uses the interface defined in class.h, it knows where to go to look for the implementation. Of course when everything is linked together, it's all binary and none of the abstractions really matter, but that's beside the point.

Classes can also be forward-declared like so:

class Class;

You would do that in a header file when the compiler can't otherwise know that Class exists.

>"and it worked if the class was above main. but let's say I have my class below main"

Let's get this straight, you should never define main() anywhere but at the bottom of the file. No exceptions. Nothing should go below it. main should be in its own file, and if it shares a file with other functions, then main should be at the bottom. Always. That's the convention, and it isn't wise to go against it. It doesn't make sense to put something below main. And the reason is because main is the only part of the program whose name isn't chosen by the programmer. It's the hard-coded entry point of the program that you will not care about when you are reading your source code. So for readability's sake, it should be isolated from the rest of the code in an easy to find, yet out of the way, location.

Take DWM's source code (http://git.suckless.org/dwm/tree/dwm.c) for example. Where do you see main?

Right. It's exactly where it should be. Despite every other function being meticulously alphabetized, main is still tucked away at the bottom.

When you call a function you must have told the compiler that there exist such a function by declaring it above, but the compiler doesn't yet need to know what the function does, so you can define it below (or in a different file) if you want.
textOriginal: When you call a function you must have told the compiler that there exist such a function by declaring it above, but the compiler doesn't yet need to know what the function does, so you can define it below (or in a different file) if you want.

textDisplay:
@LapisSea Yeah, I mean a register on a computer is usually 8 bits so there's really no way around that. That's why C doesn't have boolean types and uses ints instead since there's no advantage to creating a bool type other than readability. 

I can't say for sure why modern compilers still use function prototypes but I suspect it's because C++ compilers are much faster this way. Instead of searching through the entire program could be thousands  / millions of lines, we simply declare that a function exists and look for it in a header's respect C++ file when it's needed. This is better than looking through every single file when a function is called.

Defining a function before you call it will be much faster for the compiler. Doing so might be considered more tedious but it pays off. C++ compilers are meant to be fast. C/C++ are one of the fastest languages for general use, and is much faster than java at compiling. textDisplay:
Also, you can "get things back" from a function without it returning anything. Send a pointer or refence into it. The return value is just one feature of a function, but you don't have to use it.
And this is important to note, when making a fucntion. If, for example, you function creas a new object in RAM, and then returns a pointer ot that object, there is nothing guaranteeing taht whoever called the function actually uses the return value.
So now you've got a memory leak, congratulations. So be careful about using the return for sending important things. Instead, force the caller to send a pointer as an argument, which means he/she cannot ignore it. He/she can still fuck it up, but it's less likely.

textDisplay:
\n and endl is the same. The only difference is you can use \n to make a new line inside what you to write, eg: cout << "Hello \n World"; Will print out:
Hello
world
Endl is the same, but you cant write it inside of your text, so you have to do this: cout << "Hello" << endl;
cout << "world" << endl; to get the same result as above.

Sometimes, you'll create a function after the function is called, and it may not need to be created before, forexample I create a function called render(). I then need to call this function in another function all run() however render is created before run() as run() has a higher priority therefore is towards the top of the C++ file (programmer preference) therefore by prototype or referencing the function at the top it allows any method to call this function.

As you progress with Programming you'll understand more.

textDisplay:
C++ will be of more use in the industry, due to it being an 'industry-standard' programming language whereas Java isn't used as much. 

I mostly see Java being used on web-servers as opposed to Games please not that just because Minecraft uses Java doesn't mean AAA Studios like CryTek do.

Most Game Engines (CryEngine, Unreal Engine) use C++ so if you're looking at getting into the industry then I'd recommend learning C/C++ and getting your hands on an engine CryEngine or Unreal Engine are great and looking through the source-code and try adding functionality and write some Games using the engine.

UDK is free although doesn't support C++ as Unreal have created their on scripting language UnrealScript, CryEngine SDK is free and I do believe C++ is support however if you've got enough money rent these engines and look at the code.

If you're wondering if you should trust me, I've got experience in the industry and therefore am a reliable source.
textOriginal:

Most Game Engines (CryEngine, Unreal Engine) use C++ so if you're looking at getting into the industry then I'd recommend learning C/C++ and getting your hands on an engine CryEngine or Unreal Engine are great and looking through the source-code and try adding functionality and write some Games using the engine.

UDK is free although doesn't support C++ as Unreal have created their on scripting language UnrealScript, CryEngine SDK is free and I do believe C++ is support however if you've got enough money rent these engines and look at the code.
